## Technology

We use the `hono` framework, with the `@hono/zod-openapi` extension for OpenAPI support. All code is written in TypeScript.

## Conventions

Routes are located in `apps/api/src/routes` and are named based on their URL path. For example:

- a route at `/v1/auth` would be in `apps/api/src/routes/auth.ts`.
- a route at `/v1/auth/register` would be in `apps/api/src/routes/authRegister.ts`.
- a route at `/v1/bottles/:bottleId` would be in `apps/api/src/routes/bottleDetails.ts`.
- a route at `/v1/bottles/:bottleId/tastings` would be in `apps/api/src/routes/bottleTastings.ts`

When importing these modules, we name then accordingly:

- `authRoute` for `apps/api/src/routes/auth.ts`
- `bottleDetailsRoute` for `apps/api/src/routes/bottleDetails.ts`

Most importantly, paths are always in unique modules. Every `url` in a single route definition should be identical, and subpaths should be in their own separate module and route definition.

Routes are registered in `apps/api/src/app.ts`, by adding a new `app.route`. Routes are always registered as the last thing on the Hono instance. They are grouped together and sorted alphabetically by route prefix. For example:

```ts
import authRoute from "./routes/auth";
import bottleDetailRoute from "./routes/bottleDetails";

// ... app configuration calls

app.route("/v1/auth", authRoutes);
app.route("/v1/bottles/:bottleId", bottleDetailRoutes);
```

All unique paths should also be unique modules. For example:

- GET /v1/auth should be in `[..]/auth.ts`.
- POST /v1/auth should be in `[..]/auth.ts`.
- POST /v1/auth/register should be in `[..]/authRegister.ts`.

Tests should live side-by-side with the routes:

- If the route is at `[...]/auth.ts` the tests should be in `[...]/auth.test.ts`

## Route Definition

Routes are created as a `OpenAPIHono` instance, using the `@hono/zod-openapi` extension:

```ts
import { OpenAPIHono } from "@hono/zod-openapi";

export default new OpenAPIHono()
  .openapi(
    {
      method: "get",
      path: "/",
      responses: {
        200: {
          content: {
            "application/json": {
              schema: z.object({ ok: z.boolean() }),
            },
          },
          description: "A description of the endpoint",
        },
      },
    },
    async function (c) {
      return c.json({ ok: true });
    },
  )
  .openapi(
    {
      method: "post",
      path: "/",
      responses: {
        200: {
          content: {
            "application/json": {
              schema: z.object({ echo: z.string() }),
            },
          },
          description: "A description of the endpoint",
        },
      },
    },
    async function (c) {
      const { echo } = c.req.valid("json");

      return c.json({ echo });
    },
  );
```

### Error Responses

When returning errors from routes, such as an HTTP 401 Unauthorized response, you should use exceptions for control flow via the `http-errors-enhanced` package.

```ts
import { UnauthorizedError } from "http-errors-enhanced";

throw new UnauthorizedError("Invalid credentials.");
```

This will be caught by the error handler and converted to the appropriate HTTP response.

You'll also need to define these in the OpenAPI route responses:

```typescript
import { UnauthorizedError, unauthorizedSchema } from "http-errors-enhanced";
import { requireAuth } from "@peated/api/middleware/auth";
import { OpenAPIHono } from "@hono/zod-openapi";

export default new OpenAPIHono()
  .openapi(
    {
      method: "get",
      path: "/",
      responses: {
        401: unauthorizedSchema,
      },
    },
    async function (c) {
      throw new UnauthorizedError();
    },
  )
```

### Authentication

Authentication can be added to an endpoint view a few middlewares. These are all found in `apps/api/src/middleware`. Commonly you will use something like `requireAuth` or `requireAdmin`. These are defined in the `openapi` call:

You also must define the appropriate responses if you're requiring authorization, such as the `401` response. Utilize the `UnauthorizedError` for these responses.

Both the standard response schema, and the error class can be found in `http-errors-enhanced`.

```ts
import { UnauthorizedError, unauthorizedSchema } from "http-errors-enhanced";
import { requireAuth } from "@peated/api/middleware/auth";
import { OpenAPIHono } from "@hono/zod-openapi";

export default new OpenAPIHono()
  .openapi(
    {
      method: "get",
      path: "/",
      responses: {
        200: {
          content: {
            "application/json": {
              schema: z.object({ ok: z.boolean() }),
            },
          },
          description: "A description of the endpoint",
        },
        401: unauthorizedSchema,
      },
      // if the endpoint requires authentication, force it via
      // the middleware
      middleware: [requireAuth],
    },
    async function (c) {
      // you can fetch the authenticated user via `c.get("uesr")` 
      const currentUser = c.get("user");
      if (!currentUser) {
        throw new UnauthorizedError();
      }

      return c.json({ ok: true });
    },
  )
```

### Versioning

We're currently building `v1` of the API, meaning we will register all routes with the `/v1` prefix.

This should _only_ be defined in the `app.route` call with the `prefix` option.




